         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">14/10/87. ¶  ¶ In sending more proof of my poor "Key", ¶  dear Prof. Gray, you will see, that I had some misgivings in retaining the name Geranium Carolinianum, and thought it safer, to return to the ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">87.10.14</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Asa Gray</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Gray Herbarium Archives, Harvard University, Cambridge, Massachusetts.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">14/10/87.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In sending more proof of my poor "Key",<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B88.11.02.</p>
               </note> dear Prof. Gray, you will see, that I had some misgivings in retaining the name <name key="Geranium%20Carolinianum">Geranium Carolinianum</name>, and thought it safer, to return to the original specific appellation of G. pilosum for the widely distributed Australian plant.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See note in B88.11.02, p. 152, under <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Geranium%20pilosum">Geranium pilosum</name>
                     </seg>. M had earlier maintained <seg style="font-style: italic; ">G. carolinianum</seg> in his <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Census</seg> (B83.03.04, p. 13).</p>
               </note> Here it is never annual, simply perhaps, as we have no severe winter; but the exact position of several allied forms needs to be studied from American material; and altho' such is in my own collection, much through your generosity, and is also in Sonder's largely extant, it would be best, that American local experience ought to be brought to bear on the subject.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Perhaps one of your many disciples would institute researches in this direction.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Can you kindly inform me, what is the exact position of the radicle of <name key="Sterculia%20Mexicana">Sterculia Mexicana</name>?</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Geranium%20Carolinianum">Geranium Carolinianum</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Geranium%20pilosum">Geranium pilosum</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Sterculia%20Mexicana">Sterculia Mexicana</name>
            </p>
         </div>
